issue.title: The provided manager was not found in any slot.
issue.body:
I'm having a similar issue, and the build fails with the following trace running in Azure Devops hosted agents:

```
##[error]DiscoveryMessage : System.InvalidOperationException: The provided manager was not found in any slot.
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.ParallelOperationManager`3.ClearCompletedSlot(TManager completedManager)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.ParallelOperationManager`3.RunNextWork(TManager completedManager)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.Parallel.ParallelProxyDiscoveryManager.HandlePartialDiscoveryComplete(IProxyDiscoveryManager proxyDiscoveryManager, Int64 totalTests, IEnumerable`1 lastChunk, Boolean isAborted)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.Parallel.ParallelDiscoveryEventsHandler.HandleDiscoveryComplete(DiscoveryCompleteEventArgs discoveryCompleteEventArgs, IEnumerable`1 lastChunk)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.ProxyDiscoveryManager.InitializeDiscovery(DiscoveryCriteria discoveryCriteria, ITestDiscoveryEventsHandler2 eventHandler, Boolean skipDefaultAdapters)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.CrossPlatEngine.Client.ProxyDiscoveryManager.DiscoverTests(DiscoveryCriteria discoveryCriteria, ITestDiscoveryEventsHandler2 eventHandler)
```

The issue started when moving from 17.5 to 17.6 two days ago.

_Originally posted by @jeromelaban in https://github.com/microsoft/vstest/issues/4467#issuecomment-1553272768_



_Update_: To clarify this issue for future implementation of a fix. When testhost crashes in initialization, we don't communicate back that initialization did not happen and try to continue to the next step, which again does initialization and fails again. This will trigger cleanup 2 times via CompletedRun event, which cleans slots and pushes next work to be executed. First the cleanup will succeed, but the second one will fail. This also highlights that there is a disconnect between the work being done, and when we think the work already completed.

comment.body:
> Thank you, @MarcoRossignoli and @nohwnd! It works as proposed to mark all projects which reference `nUnit` package but do not contain test cases:
> 
> ```diff
> +    <!-- Exclude this project from the list of tests project -->
> +    <TestProject>false</TestProject>
> +    <IsTestProject>false</IsTestProject>
> ```

Thank you! Been pulling my hair out for the last day. I have both NET6 and Framework and 'Microsoft Unit Testing Framework for C++' tests in my solution and this issue has been a real problem

issue.title: vstest.console not able to load Microsoft.DiaSymReader during execution
issue.body:
## Description
We have .NET Framework Test projects which are referencing NuGet packages for NUnit and NUnitTestAdapter. All those test project are able to run in VS 2022 correctly when they are setup that way. When we will try to run same test projects over vstest.console on same computer where VS itself is installed we will end up in situation where runner will say that binaries dont contains any tests.  If NuGet Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk is added to single test project in solution (8 test projects in total) and recompiled. vstest.console is miraculously able to run all tests from all projects afterwards.

However, when we are trying to do exactly same in AzureDevops pipeline while we are using VSTest@2 it doesnt matter if Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk is or is not included in single or all projects. Execution will fail with error "Failed to load extensions from file 'D:\B\2\4\s\bin\x64\Debug\NUnit3.TestAdapter.dll'. Please use /diag for more information." 

In detailed log (we can provide it) following errors are logged.
TpTrace Verbose: 0 : 4640, 1, 2023/10/20, 08:44:40.104, 7243901507794, vstest.console.exe, MetadataReaderExtensionsHelper: Discovering extensions inside assembly 'Microsoft.DiaSymReader, Version=1.4.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31bf3856ad364e35' file path 'C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\Enterprise\Common7\IDE\Extensions\TestPlatform\Extensions\Microsoft.DiaSymReader.dll'
TpTrace Information: 0 : 4640, 1, 2023/10/20, 08:44:40.104, 7243901544329, vstest.console.exe, AssemblyResolver.OnResolve: Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64: Resolving assembly.
TpTrace Information: 0 : 4640, 1, 2023/10/20, 08:44:40.104, 7243901545205, vstest.console.exe, AssemblyResolver.OnResolve: Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64: Searching in: 'C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\Enterprise\Common7\IDE\Extensions\TestPlatform\Extensions'.
TpTrace Information: 0 : 4640, 1, 2023/10/20, 08:44:40.119, 7243901706136, vstest.console.exe, AssemblyResolver.OnResolve: Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64: Failed to load assembly. Reason:System.BadImageFormatException: Could not load file or assembly 'Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64.dll' or one of its dependencies. The module was expected to contain an assembly manifest.
File name: 'Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64.dll' ---> System.BadImageFormatException: Could not load file or assembly 'Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64.dll' or one of its dependencies. The module was expected to contain an assembly manifest.
File name: 'Microsoft.DiaSymReader.Native.amd64.dll'


   at System.Reflection.AssemblyName.nGetFileInformation(String s)
   at System.Reflection.AssemblyName.GetAssemblyName(String assemblyFile)
   at Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform.Common.Utilities.AssemblyResolver.OnResolve(Object sender, AssemblyResolveEventArgs args)

## Expected behavior
Tests will run.

## Actual behavior
vstest.console not able to run tests as its not able to load Microsoft.DiaSymReader

## Environment
VS 2022 17.6 when running from VS itself or commandline. Or VSTest@2 with 2022 17.6 build setup.

[TestRunDiag.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/vstest/files/13054211/TestRunDiag.txt)

comment.body:
The host log says:

Failed to load extensions from file 'D:\B\2\5\s\bin\x64\Debug\NUnit3.TestAdapter.dll'.  Skipping test extension scan for this file.  Error: System.IO.FileLoadException: Could not load file or assembly 'System.Runtime, Version=4.2.2.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a' or one of its dependencies. The located assembly's manifest definition does not match the assembly reference. (Exception from HRESULT: 0x80131040)


This is an error message that you would see when .NET Core dll is trying to load into .NET Framework process. Your testhost is .NET Framework 48, because your project is detected as .NET Framework 48.

So there are 3 options: 

1. You are stripping TargetFrameworkAttribute from your test dll somewhere in build, and it is detected incorrectly as .NET framework. This is unlikely because I would expect to see .NET Framework 462 host in that case. You can double check by opening your dll in ilspy.
![image](https://github.com/microsoft/vstest/assets/5735905/45f151a1-56a4-44f6-8a0f-bb5a3e70cd61)


2. You are mixing your dependencies somewhere in the build. But I don't see any of your test dlls in this run being detected as .NET (Core). So I don't know which project that dll would come from.

3. VStest is scraping all your test projects for dlls and links this into your project. Also unlikely, the DLL is in the same folder as your test projects. 

So I would start by downloading the folder of your build, and double checked with ILspy (as shown above), what is the target framework of you test dll, and what is the target framework of the NUnit3.TestAdpater.dll in that same folder. 


repro: 

You can simply dotnet build, and then copy the nunit3.testadapter.dll from the net8.0 bin to net48. Run with `dotnet test <path to the dll> --diag:logs\` and you will see the same error in log. 
[mixup.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/vstest/files/13186235/mixup.zip)

comment.body: @Evangelink, replying here as well. As per our offline chat, merging was partially necessary for testing. Local testing won't work since the branch name is a parameter passed by the pipeline, and on the PR build the branch was named "merge". Not empty anymore, but not what was expected either. However, I looked at the official build running after we merged this change and I can see it performed the check and the branch is indeed called 'main'.
